":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry de Champernon was born about 1145, in Ilfracombe, Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, Jordan DeChampernon, was 37 and his mother, Mabera DeCaen, was 37. He married Rohese de Tracy about 1169. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died about 1203, in Devon, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 60."},"et":{"Abt 1145–Abt 1203":"umbes 1145–umbes 1203","1145–1203":"1145–1203","–1203":"–1203","1148–1237":"1148–1237","1171–1232":"1171–1232","1173–1255":"1173–1255","1109–1172":"1109–1172","1109–1190":"1109–1190","1190":"1190","WFT Est. 1166-1255":"umbes 1166 kuni 1255","About:1173-00-00":"umbes 1173","Abt 1203":"umbes 1203","1173":"1173","1172":"1172","1171":"1171","1237":"1237","1148":"1148","1203":"1203","Abt 1145":"umbes 1145","1255":"1255","1145":"1145","1232":"1232","1109":"1109","estimated 1169":"umbes 1169","of Clist Champernon, Devonshire, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bamstaple, Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","